title: For Sale:  M1 Aiming Circle from WWII
postcontent: This is a vintage M1 Aiming Circle from World War II, it is made primarily of brass, and appears to be in working condition. Aiming circles are basically telescopes which are used to measure for exact azimuth and elevation. They helped the army artillery units strike their targets with accuracy. This piece still has its original, military green paint and is marked "Circle, Aiming, Ml, No. 8237, FM., 1942". It is mounted on a base that allows the unit to turn for viewing. It was stored away for decades. The levels are intact and not cracked or otherwise broken. The optics are in very good condition. It's a very nice piece of World War II history! $150. Largo, FL. postcontent: This is a Creedmoor Sports rifle that they had done for them on a limited run by Rock Ridge Machine Works available by preorder only. There were made for the CMP Vintage Sniper Team Match. As said before these were only done in limited numbers. It is brand new never been fired. It was purchased by myself with the intent of competing in the Vintage Sniper Team Match. Although that never came to be. Its been sitting in the plastic bag it originally came in with a rust preventitave stick in the barrel, and then that wrapped in a silicone impregnated sock in the closet for over 3 years. It has everything that came with it from Creedmoor Sports, threaded lense caps, scope spring, papers, everything. It is even in the box it was shipped in from Creedmoor Sports. I also have a M1903 Air Service Rifle Magazine for sale with the rifle as well. Air Service Magazines are extremely rare and equally expensive. They were designed for the use of the M1903 rifle out of the back of biplanes. As the soldier was unable to reload easily the magazine would afford him 20 extra rounds on top of the 5 the rifle held internally. Bringing the total capacity to 25 rounds. It is affixed to the rifle by removing the trigger guard, depressing the floor plate button, removing the floor plate and replacing it with the magazine. Then reinstalling the trigger guard and magazine as a whole. The Air Service Magazine is an extra $600 added to the rifle price if interested. More pictures are available upon request. Thanks for looking.
